

The UDS (Utilization Data Submission) pipeline answers one simple question: "How much money does Blue Shield save its PPO members through negotiated rates?"

Every month, we pull a full year of medical claims - about 41 million billing lines — and run them through 14 processing steps. Each step applies real-world business logic: repricing claims using negotiated fee schedules, recovering wrongly denied claims, protecting patients from surprise bills, and removing surcharges. What comes out the other end is a clean, audited dataset of ~25–30 million claims showing what providers billed versus what Blue Shield actually pays. The result: a ~60% discount — for every $1.00 a doctor or hospital bills, members only owe about $0.40. This report is sent to an independent actuarial firm (Milliman) as a regulatory requirement.

reviously, this entire process ran on a legacy SAS platform — expensive annual licensing, single-node processing, manual multi-script execution, and zero built-in error checking. The migration to Databricks eliminates SAS licensing costs entirely, replaces fragile manual steps with automated process validation across all 14 pipeline stages, and reduces configuration for each new reporting cycle to a single date change in one config file. The pipeline now runs on scalable Spark infrastructure with Delta Lake guarantees (no corrupted or half-written outputs), full version control, and an embedded knowledge-transfer guide — making it auditable, reproducible, and maintainable by any team member, not just the original author. In short: lower cost, faster execution, fewer errors, and complete auditability — all while processing the same regulatory workload on modern, enterprise-grade infrastructure.
